The Byron School District would like to thank Byron Bank for their generous donation of $2,000 to help fund tents throughout the school campus. The tents are an additional safety precaution aimed at providing alternative areas for our students staff to conduct class or eat lunch during the school day. Pictured (left to right) is Mr. Christian Kerr, Byron CUSD Business Manager, Mr. Zack Ettelbrick, Byron Principal, and Mr. Sean Considine, Byron Bank.

post_text:
FFA Takes 2nd Place!

Because of COVID all in person FFA State Contests were cancelled, however the State did an excellent job of providing virtual contests. While not as good as live because it couldn't test the students abilities in hands on skills, it was still very challenging. The Byron FFA Horticulture Team took 2nd place in the State! Individuals were: Alex Buseski 3rd, Ally Keefe 4th, Renee Gehrke 18th, and Ryan Bendit 24th. Very impressive, especially since Mr. Tryggestad could not help them prepare. The students really did it all on their own. There are also National competitions for all FFA contests and usually only the State Champion goes on to compete. However our state Horticulture contest actually combines 2 National Contests (Nursery/Landscape and Floriculture). Because of this the top 2 teams go on to represent Illinois at the National Contests. Byron will be representing Illinois when the National Contests return.

Congratulations and good luck! You have made us proud!

Senior Reccognition

The Byron Boosters Association Scholarship
Association has established this award to both emphasize the organization’s commitment to post- secondary education/training as well as to recognize a graduating senior or seniors who have made significant and positive contributions to Byron High School (BHS hereafter) athletics and/or extracurricular activities. This scholarship is given annually to a senior or seniors deemed worthy upon the review of applications by the Scholarship Committee.

This year's recipients are Alivia Bradford and Abbie McKinley!

Alivia will be attending George Williams College of Aurora University and will be majoring in nursing. GWC has also offered Alivia the Presidential Scholarship which provides full tuition.

Abbie will be beginning her college career at Rock Valley College where she plans to major in Early Childhood Education. RVC has awarded Abbie the Blaine Auker Memorial Scholarship.

Congratulations to Abbie and Alivia!

The Byron Lodge was founded in 1858 and is the oldest continuing organization in Byron. Byron Lodge was founded in 1858 and is the oldest continuing organization in Byron. Senior Recognition Week

Rotary Club of Byron is proud to award the 2020 $1,000 Bob Adams Service Above Self Scholarship to Kennedy Markham!
Bob Adams was a charter member of Rotary who worked tirelessly to uphold Rotary’s mission of empowering others. In awarding this scholarship to Kennedy, the selection committee noted that, like Bob Adams, Kennedy is at her best when she is empowering others.
When spends her free time working with students challenged by disabilities; when she is on the basketball court, playing as a personal assistant to a Special Olympian; when she is developing Byron’s first student special education internship; when she is volunteering at a VA hospital in North Carolina; when she is setting up a food pantry in Appalachia – Kennedy is using her gifts to empower others!

Rotary Club of Byron is confident that Kennedy will continue to uphold the group’s mission of Service Above Self as she continues her education.

Congratulations Kennedy and best of luck as you pursue a career in special education!

Senior Recognition Week

Each year, the Byron Education Association awards a scholarship in honor of Michael Jerding, a former teacher who passed away in the midst of his career. The members of the BEA are firmly committed to the students of the Byron school district and hope to honor the legacy of Michael Jerding and all of the current members by offering scholarship money to help support students’ success at the college level. Students were asked to complete an application process to articulate how the aspects of TIGER PRIDE have impacted them and how they will continue to carry out that mission in their post-high school endeavors. This year, the committee selected 5 recipients. The committee would like to thank all students who put energy into the application process. This year’s recipients are Alivia Bradford, Madeleine Brass, Kennedy Markham, Kate Mumma, & Brock Wilson. Congratulations!!

post_text: The John Philip Sousa award, introduced in 1955, is to honor the top student in the high school band and recognizes students with superior musicianship and outstanding dedication. The Byron High School band is proud to present this award to Madie Libman. Madie participated in all possible band ensembles including the musical pit orchestra on the cello, jazz band on the bass guitar, marching band and symphonic band on the flute for 4 years. Madie’s knowledge and understanding of music allowed her to appreciate music and performances on a deeper level and her dedication to the Byron High School band along with her eagerness to share her love of music with others makes her a very deserving recipient of this award. I would like to thank the Music Boosters for their scholarship given to the recipient of this award every year. Congratulations Madie!

post_text:
The Louis Armstrong Jazz Award, inaugurated in 1974 after the death of this great jazz artist, is given to outstanding jazz musicians at each high school. The Byron High School band is proud to present this award to Geoffrey Van Heeren. Geoffrey participated in jazz band throughout all of his middle school and high school band years on the trumpet. Geoffrey was always eager to learn and perform solos with the jazz band. He was also continuously learning more and increasing his improvisation skills. His favorite part of jazz band is improvising the 12 bar blues. Geoffrey’s dedication and commitment to learning more complex music skills make him a very worthy recipient of this award. I would like to thank the Music Boosters for their scholarship given to the recipient of this award every year.

Geoffrey will be attending Eastern Illinois University next fall majoring in Digital Media.

Congratulations Geoffrey!

Senior Recognition Week

Mathematical Science and Artistic Achievement Awards

Each year, the BHS mathematics department selects one individual who has not only excelled in the field of mathematics...but has also exhibited a passion for the deep analytical nature of mathematics. To "figure it out" is one of the most fundamentally important skills of our species. While we also look for dedication, the ability to challenge oneself, and mathematical ability...it is the sense of wonder when problem solving that we cherish above all others. We are very pleased to announce the 2020 Mathematical Science award goes to Kennedy Turner!

In addition...the recipient of the artistic achievement award is chosen based on creative growth over the course of four years in the art and design program at Byron High School. This award is also going to Kennedy Turner.

Congratulations to Kennedy and we look forward to following your journey at St. Louis University as you pursue your degree in Biomedical Engineering!

Physical Science Award

Every year, the science department selects an individual who has excelled above and beyond in the field of physics and chemistry during his or her time at BHS. This individual must not only exhibit an excellent understanding of material in those courses...but also must have an unquenchable desire to understand our universe and our place in it. It is with great pride that we award this year's Physical Science Award to Brock Wilson! Congrats, Brock!

post_text:
Senior Recognition Week

Congratulations to Gaven Featherston! He is the recipient of the Daniel Edwards Memorial Scholarship.

Message from Ronald and Rosemarie Edwards:

"This scholarship is being given in honor of our son, Daniel Edwards, who graduated from Byron High School in 2017 and passed away in 2018. From a young age Daniel showed a passion for working with his hands by disassembling and redesigning his skateboards to find the perfect ride. His passion for adventure and curiosity for how things worked was at the center of all his activities.

After graduation Daniel continued his education through the auto mechanic program at Kishwaukee College. That is why this scholarship is geared toward someone pursuing a career in auto/diesel mechanics or another trade.

Please help us congratulate this year's Daniel Edwards Memorial Scholarship winner Gaven M. Featherston." ~Ronald and Rosemarie Edwards

"The dictionary is the only place where success comes before work." - Vince Lombardi

post_text:
Renee Gehrke was elected as Section 2 FFA President tonight. The amount of extra work this young lady has put in just to reach this position is amazing, beyond COVID! As Section 2 President Renee will serve the 13 chapters she represents in our area at the state level. This is the highest officer position a high school FFA student can hold. Renee has been working towards this goal since she expressed her interest in 7th grade. She will hopefully be traveling in person to represent Ogle and Lee counties in Springfield this summer and all next year.

On a separate but also great achievement: Carter Conderman was also elected as the Section 2 Secretary to serve on this area’s FFA Officer Team. This is the first time Byron has had 2 students serve in these regional leadership offices at the same time!

post_text: This Friday, November 8th Byron Schools will be having their Veterans Day ceremonies at the schools. The MS assembly begins at 8:30 am and should last 45 to 60 mins. post_text: On Friday, these BHS students volunteered their time to assist with the Gold Star 500 Endurance Cycling Event, which made a rest stop at the Byron Fire Protection District Station. Cyclists rode 125 miles each day over the course of 4 days. The event honors the service and sacrifice of nearly 300 service men and women from Illinois who gave their lives in Iraq and Afghanistan and helps raise funds for Gold Star Families.

BIG UNIFORM SALE!!!!!

Several former Byron uniforms worn throughout the years will be for sale for $1 on August 15th, from 4pm – 8pm in the Byron Middle School cafeteria. This sale is open to the public and is also Back to School Night. Uniforms from all sports teams are available. Huge selection… Great ideas for Halloween, dress up, memorabilia to display, etc.. Lots of small sizes for the little ones as well. All proceeds will go towards new athletic equipment and student organizations supplies.

post_text: The FFA and Ag Dept will once again have a plant sale starting this Friday. Sunday is Mother's Day so guys don't forget that. We will have hanging baskets available for $20 and a wide variety of vegetables, annuals, and perennials available. First come = First serve. Many things sold out last year so come early to make sure you get what you want. Sale is all day Friday until 5:30, and the Following week until 5. All plants were grown and maintained by my Horticulture Class.

Please be aware that weed control and fertilization of the lawns at all District 226 schools will take place on Saturday, May 4, 2019 through Sunday, May 5, 2019 weather permitting.

Illinois law (Lawn Care Products Application and Notification Act) requires all school districts to notify students and staff when lawn care chemicals are being used in or around school facilities.

We are committed to minimizing the use of chemicals for weed control and lawn care, but at times, it is necessary for the proper maintenance of the facility. If you have any questions about the application of the lawn fertilizer, please contact Mr. Brent Hall, Director of Buildings and Grounds, at (815) 234-5491 Ext 267.

post_text:
Monday and Tuesday students were able to interact with pig lungs in health class to better understand the dangers associated with smoking. Students were able to compare/contrast a healthy lung to that of a “smoker’s” lung. Within the blackened lung students were able to see and feel a cancerous tumor (one of many side effects from tobacco use).
IL State Objectives:
22.B.4a- Explain social and economic effects of health problems on individuals and society.
23.B.4a- Explain immediate and long term effects of health habits on the body systems.
24.B.5a- Explain immediate and long term impacts of health decisions to the individual, family, and community.
